// `import name as local_name;` is NOT scpp syntax. It briefly appeared in
// ch11 §11.8 as a proposed feature, but turned out to not be real C++20
// syntax (only `import name;`/`import name:part;` are standard) and was
// removed as a documentation bug (commit 0413530) -- scpp intentionally
// introduces no syntax beyond real C++. Since this is exactly the kind of
// thing a Python/Rust programmer might instinctively try, it's still
// worth confirming scpp rejects it as a clean compile error rather than
// crashing or being silently misparsed. The aliasing target module
// doesn't even need to exist for this to be exercised: the rejection
// happens at parse time, before any module resolution.
import foo as bar;

int main() {
    return 0;
}
